ODE V.

Wn used to think the Thunderer reigned supreme In heaven and earth3 but Caesar now must be Our chief and present Deity3 Since subject to his rule all nations seem, From Britain's distant isle to broad Euphrates’ stream.

Hath then the Roman soldier dared In ties of kindred to unite With hostile tribes ’gainst whom he warr'd When Crassus led him to the fight? And have Apulia’s sons grown grey In wedlock with an alien wife, And spent a base, inglorious life Under the Median tyrant’s sway? Oh! change unknown, till this degen'rate day!
